<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="nouns">@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}</a> is used to list example nouns in the same way that <a href="grammar-particle-ya.html">@HI{{ya}}</a> is used.
However, @HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}
is more informal. Furthermore, @HI{{@EM{{toka}}}} can sometimes follow the last noun listed, which @HI{{ya}}
never can.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{donnna@KT{{supo-tsu}}woshiteimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{soudesune.@KT{{tenisu}}@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}@KJ{{water^swim}}@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}...}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: What kind of sports do you do?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Well ... playing tennis, swimming and so on.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="sentences">As</a> well as enumerating nouns, @HI{{@EM{{toka}}}} can list whole sentences.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{child}}domonotoki,@KJ{{mama}}ni[@FG{{@KJ{{exertion^strong}}:benkyou}}shiro]@EM{{toka}}[takusan'@KJ{{eat}}benasai]@EM{{toka}}
      yoku@KJ{{say}}waremashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      When I was a child, I was often told by my mother to "Go and study", "Eat up" and so on.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The construction @Splain{{}}@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}@Splain{{}}@HI{{@EM{{toka}}suru}} is used to refer to something in general.
It would be inappropriate in the example above if it were referring to things that the child was told on a specific occasion.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}} can follow  pairs of words of opposite meaning to indicate uncertainty.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}hasonotokiniyotte,@KJ{{attend^matter}}ga@KJ{{mask^white}}i@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}
      @KJ{{mask^white}}kunai@HI{{@EM{{toka}}}}@KJ{{say}}unode,dochiranokawakarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Depending on which day it is, she says she likes her work or she doesn't like it, so I don't know whether she does or not.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="uncertainty">When</a> @HI{{@EM{{toka}}}} is followed by @HI{{@KJ{{say}}u}}, it is no longer a conjunction.
It is a quote marker followed by a @HI{{ka}} which indicates the speaker's uncertainty.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{assistant^wisteria}}:satou}}sanha@KJ{{busy}}shikute@KJ{{going}}kenai@EM{{toka@KJ{{say}}tteita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Sato was saying he can't go there because he's busy or something.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@N1{{}}@EM{{toka@KJ{{say}}u}}@N2{{}}}} is another construction that uses @HI{{@EM{{toka}}@KJ{{say}}u}} to indicate uncertainty.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{plains^mouth}}:noguchi}}@EM{{toka@KJ{{say}}u}}@FG{{@KJ{{person}}:hito}}ga@KJ{{come}}ta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A person named Noguchi or something like that showed up.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When used with nouns @HI{{@EM{{toka}}}} has a more informal feel than @HI{{ya}}.
</p>

